Alot of people asked me to share my diet that's helped me with my blood sugars and weight it's called the georgina diet a diet my dr named after me  Breakfast is 2 morning star veggie links 1 egg any style 1 cup watermelon 3/4 cup bran cereal but i use any flavor special k cereal 3/4 cup 1 percent or 2 percent milk Lunch is 4 carrot sticks 1 oz cheese 1/2cup watermelon or any kind of melon you like 1 can tuna/salmon or chicken i do a special piece of cooked boneless chicken Dinner is unlimited kale salad but only 2 tbsp dressing 1 cup lentil soup but i found a healthy greens soup i like or any soup that has good amount of fiber in it make your own if you want i also have a awesome lentil and barley soup recipe my kids love that way I can control the amount of sodium in it and then a small piece of chicken i cook it and put into my kale salad along with the tomatoes and whatever other veggies i put into the salad also drink plenty of water which helps lower blood sugars i never been a big fan of plain water so I make sassy water which is 10 cups of water in a pitcher 1 cucumber peeled or unpeeled and sliced up 1 lemon sliced up a piece of ginger peeled and shredded and 12 or more mint leaves put in fridge over night drink all the next day my blood sugar was almost 11 before doing this diet was looking at having to do insulin but after working on my stress level dropping some weight my blood sugars dropped down to the low 7s  i hope this can help someone i was once told to take 200 milgrams metformin but to many side affects i only  do 500 with breakfast 500 with dinner i do the diet 5 days a week and eat sensibly on the weekends it's about fiber measuring and reading labels looking for grams of sugar for me

Cabbage and Sausage Ingredients 1 lb kielbasa smoked sausage 1 1/2 tbsps olive oil, divided 1 medium onion, chopped 3 garlic cloves, minced 1 medium head cabbage, cored and chopped into 1-inch pieces (about 2 lbs) 3/4 tsp kosher salt, plus more to taste 1/2 tsp freshly ground black pepper 1 tsp red wine vinegar Instructions Halve the kielbasa lengthwise and then slice it into 1/2-inch pieces. Heat a large deep skillet or dutch oven over medium heat.  Add 1/2 tablespoon oil and the kielbasa. Toss to coat and then cook until browned, about 3 minutes per side. Transfer the kielbasa to a plate. Return the pan to the stove and reduce the heat to medium low. Add the remaining tablespoon of oil and the onion. Cook, stirring occasionally, until the onion has softened. Add the garlic, cabbage, salt, and pepper. Toss well to combine. Cover and cook, stirring every 4-5 minutes until the cabbage is wilted, about 12 minutes. Stir in the vinegar and return the kielbasa to the pot. Stir and cover for about 3 more minutes, until the cabbage is tender and the kielbasa is hot. Taste and add salt, if needed. Enjoy! Notes The original recipe is written with turkey sausage. If that's your preference, it will work nicely in this recipe. My family prefers traditional kielbasa, so that is our choice for this dish. Hi! I'm new to this group, but not to keto. I thought I'd share my story. Three years ago I was miserable with joint pain, lethargy, brain fog, frequent urination, and more. I'd been in a car accident and my minorly sprained wrists wouldn't heal even after months. I was in tears when I saw my doctor to try to figure out what was going on. She ran many tests and discovered I was pre-diabetic with an A1c of 5.9 with fasting blood sugar of 120+. I'm grateful I was sensitive to high blood sugar and was symptomatic, because it caused me to seek help and motivated me to change! I immediately purged my pantry and started eating low carb. After a little while I discovered the term "keto" and improved my fat consumption. My high blood sugar symptoms started disappearing in just a few weeks. I literally didn't weigh myself for the first 6 months. My goal was blood sugar control, and I saw that steadily improving right away. Six months in, my FBS was down to 85! Then, when I realized my pants were falling off, I discovered I was down 25 lbs as well. Nice side effect ðŸ˜. My A1c has been 5.0/4.9/5.1 since adopting a ketogenic diet. Over 18 months I shed 65 lbs. This is an average of less than a pound a week, but I didn't stress and scale-watch because I knew I was in this for the long haul. Eating this way has changed my life and I look forward to reaching 40 feeling much younger than I did at 35!

Hello All,  This is my first post here.  I am a diabetic, â€œconsidered as uncontrolledâ€ by MD.  I was diagnosed in 2014, after my A1C labs came back at 8.8.  However, since I worked for Kaiser Permanente at the time, I decided to do some research on my own regarding my ailment; I read up about all of the side effects for most of the diabetes medications, hmmm.., I refused any kind of medication......I flat out told my MD not â€œFnâ€ happening. I told her I would take control of my diabetes through diet and exercise.  So I did, and within 90 days I went back to get an A1C recheck, my digits had dropped to 6.0 a significant drop.  My MD did not try to push any kind of meds on me again, she knew I was very serious about taking control and getting better.  However she was adamant that I check my BS daily and keep it within the 120 range.   So I was now on my new journey and that was for me to take care of me the best I could. Also, I truly did not plan for it, but as a side effect, I dropped 90lbs.  That definitely was not in my plans. I was not even trying to loose weight, it just happened, I had topped out at 340lbs, and started loosing what a great incentive.  I had maintained 250lbs for quite sometime, but just couldnâ€™t seem to shed anymore with what I was doing.  Of course I had never heard of IF or Keto until May of this year.  It was my son who introduced me to this way of eating.   He told me that I was basically already eating the Keto way but I should incorporate an IF plan as well.  After more research on IF and Keto, I found it to be an easy crossover for me.  I jumped right in and started immediately with an 18:6 routine, with a 44 hr Fast on the weekends.  With more research, I also found out that some of the veggies I had not given up along with a lot of fruit were detrimental to me and what I was trying to do, â€œlive longerâ€.  I then understood why my weight had stalled back then.  At that time I wasnâ€™t aware of all the other options I had available to me.   So now itâ€™s  2018 and time to retire, so what do I do, of course I managed to pack on 38lbs....I stopped my exercise, and walking, I got lazy.  So when I stepped onto the scale and looked down at the numbers, I was not very happy with myself.  I knew then that something had to change again for me because I refused to take Metformin or Insulin injections.   I am happy to say that since 5/25 of starting my new life style I have shed 20lbs of those 38lbs.    I am on a roll now, and I know now that I will make my goal of 155lbs.  Iâ€™ve been shedding 2lbs consistently since my 5/25 start; and my BS has become more stable, between 108 to 135 depending on before meals or after meals.   So I am tickled to have found another group to relate to and tell my story too and be someone elseâ€™s support if needed. Thatâ€™s my story and Iâ€™m sticking to it.
